abstract: Mayor Bill de Blasio has taken 10 rides by police chopper in the last three months. Before that, he had traveled that way a total of eight times since taking office.
snippet: Mayor Bill de Blasio has taken 10 rides by police chopper in the last three months. Before that, he had traveled that way a total of eight times since taking office.
lead_paragraph: For much of his tenure, Mayor Bill de Blasio has rarely availed himself of Police Department helicopters to get around New York City. Getting around that way, he has said, was simply not his thing.

abstract: Santiago Taveras, of DeWitt Clinton High School, joins a list of principals tasked with turning around troubled schools, only to leave or be forced out after Education Department inquiries.
snippet: Santiago Taveras, of DeWitt Clinton High School, joins a list of principals tasked with turning around troubled schools, only to leave or be forced out after Education Department inquiries.
lead_paragraph: As a deputy schools chancellor under Mayor Michael R. Bloomberg, Santiago Taveras oversaw efforts to close many of New York City’s large and troubled public high schools. Then, in 2013, he did something unusual. He took a pay cut and became a principal again, this time with the aim not of closing a school, but of saving one: DeWitt Clinton High School in the Bronx.

abstract: After months of negotiations between the de Blasio administration and the Recording Academy, the ceremony is expected to return to the city for the first time since 2003.
snippet: After months of negotiations between the de Blasio administration and the Recording Academy, the ceremony is expected to return to the city for the first time since 2003.
lead_paragraph: After a hiatus of more than a decade, the Grammy Awards are expected to return to New York in 2018, several people familiar with the city’s bid to lure the ceremony from Los Angeles said.

abstract: Following successful measures on Election Day, advocates believe more cities will consider them, not just to fight obesity, but also to bring in more money.
snippet: Following successful measures on Election Day, advocates believe more cities will consider them, not just to fight obesity, but also to bring in more money.
lead_paragraph: For more than a decade, Coca-Cola, Pepsi and other beverage companies have fought mightily against efforts to tax sugary sodas, defeating more than three dozen such proposals around the country.

abstract: Liz Mandarano, the owner of the brownstone that was the backdrop for Spike Lee’s film, believes she’s being unfairly targeted. But the city said her building violated the housing code.
snippet: Liz Mandarano, the owner of the brownstone that was the backdrop for Spike Lee’s film, believes she’s being unfairly targeted. But the city said her building violated the housing code.
lead_paragraph: The doorbell rang. On the steps of the brownstone in the Bedford-Stuyvesant section of Brooklyn were two police officers, two firefighters and two Buildings Department inspectors. The one who did the talking said to get out immediately, not because there was a gas leak, not because anyone was suspected of selling illegal drugs, but because the brownstone was being used as a bed-and-breakfast.

abstract: Despite progress on cutting down on unfair arrests, there is still a racial disparity for those charged in New York City.
snippet: Despite progress on cutting down on unfair arrests, there is still a racial disparity for those charged in New York City.
lead_paragraph: Mayor Bill de Blasio, who took office in 2014, has made some progress in cutting back on the unfair and sometimes illegal police practices under which thousands of New Yorkers are arrested every year for possessing trivial amounts of marijuana.
